  "hasSensitivityAnalysis": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/sa/hemolysis-sensitivity-power-law-viscosity",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "Sensitivity analysis: power-law exponent and blood viscosity effects on NIH",
    "description": "Sobol first-order and total-order sensitivity indices computed for the normalized index of hemolysis with respect to five input parameters: power-law exponent α (nominal 1.9), power-law coefficient C (nominal 3.62×10⁻⁷), dynamic viscosity (nominal 3.5 mPa·s), inlet flow rate, and rotational speed. The power-law exponent α accounts for 61% of NIH output variance at the 5 L/min / 3000 RPM operating point; blood viscosity contributes 18%. Interaction terms between α and C account for an additional 14% of total variance, confirming that uncertainty reduction efforts should prioritise the power-law constitutive parameters."
  },
